[Student "S"]
{Partner transfers and you naturally respond 2\S. Partner bids the \S game and you pass. 

North plays 4\S. East leads the \CQ. West plays the \C8 and your first decision is whether to hold up.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

You should certainly hold up. West is the Danger hand here because if West ever gets the lead he can play a \H through your unprotected \HK, possibly giving you two \H losers. If you take the first trick with the \CA you open the door for West to gain entry with the \CK which you know he has. 

Next pull three rounds of trumps. Fortune smiles and they split 3-2. 

Now it's time to play on \Ds. Do you finesse for the \DQ? and if so, which way do you finesse? 

Missing 6 \Ds to the Queen of course you should finesse. And you will finesse through West, of course, because he is the Danger Hand. So play dummy's \DK, then play the \D10 and let it ride.

This time West holds the \DQ and you make an overtrick, winning 4 \D tricks and discarding a \H loser from dummy.

Another time East will hold the \DQ and you will make the contract, but no overtrick. }
[Play "W"]CQ

